What is ethical bird watching?

If you love birds, likely you have seen a great buzz surrounding a snowy owl here in California. Loads of people are flocking to photograph this bird, and situations like this can actually cause harm to the animal. Birds can become harassed, disrupted from their survival behaviors such as hunting or sleep, and stressed by crowds. Birds that are far from their typical range are often under extra stress and pressures as it is. Here are some ways you can be an ethical birder and help keep wildlife safe!

•Stay at a respectful distance so that you are not distressing birds or modifying their behavior.

•Avoid advancing on birds to “make them do something”. The ideal birder goes unnoticed to the bird. 

•Avoid the use of drones, which can agitate birds. 

•Be respectful of the habitat you are in while birding. 

•Avoid luring a bird with food or playbacks just to get a photo. This creates a dangerous dynamic for wildlife. 

•If you know of a situation in which a bird is being flooded with hordes of photographers, consider not adding to this problem. 

While it is exciting to see a rare bird, it is important to put the animals’ best interests in mind. Being respectful while birding is one way we can all help protect our wildlife. 

#birdwatching
#birding
#wildlifeconservation

Hawks and eagles belong to the same family, Accipitridae.  But what exactly is the difference between the two?  In general, you will find that “eagles” are larger and more powerful birds. But it really comes down to what the bird was named. You will find very large hawks, like the ferruginous hawk (pictured), and very small eagles like the Great Nicobar serpent eagle. There is no clear taxonomic differentiation between the two, compared to other raptors like falcons or ospreys. While some traits are more common among one group like size, there is no concrete set of characteristics that separates one from the other physiologically. In general, the largest birds are named “eagle”.

Animals have very specific dietary needs, especially rapidly growing babies. This is a great message from two biologists monitoring a rookery.

Photo and post from Dr. Linda and Tom Litteral: 

“We’re all excited at the Venice Area Audubon Rookery as the first great blue heron chicks hatched this week, midway into January. Barely able to manage their wobbly heads, the two mop-topped chicks occasionally lift their heads just a few seconds to spar with each other or search for a fishy meal from a nearby adult. But much to the dismay of those watching, the adult brought forth not fish, but four hot dogs. Dr. Linda Litteral and her husband Thomas Litteral, biologists and photojournalists, documented the event. Thomas explains that well-meaning neighbors feed the adults hot dogs, who in turn feed them to their chicks. The tiny chicks swallow the hot dogs whole with some difficulty. Dr. Litteral adds that this has been occurring over and over the past several days and the chicks are not getting the proper nutrients that fish would provide. Moreover, two years ago, she noted that chicks being fed hot dogs did not reach adulthood. The Litterals cannot emphasize how important it is not to feed hot dogs or other human food to wild birds and let the birds find their own food in the wild.”

Common ravens in Southern California are extremely overpopulated, like many areas out west. Their numbers have boomed over recent decades, endangering wildlife and negatively altering ecosystems. One study states that raven populations in the Mojave Desert have increased more than 700% over the past 40 years.  The main cause of this population increase is human-provided subsidies of food, water, and nest sites. These resourceful birds are now displacing other native species and there is an imbalance of populations in the ecosystem. One example of this is the ravens’ negative effect on California’s threatened desert tortoise.

As you can see in this video, common ravens are just about everywhere in huge numbers. It really is a problem, and one that requires a higher level of management than it is currently receiving.

Even flying a falconry bird can be dangerous with all of these ravens. Cheeto knows he is safe with me.

Holding his prize, deciding where to go with the ravens hot on his tail. For whatever reason yesterday Cheeto decided to take his catch up on a boulder to eat, which instantly drew the attention of 3 nearby ravens. They chased him around trying to rob him of his sparrow, and when I got to him he was hiding in a bush. After spending some time deciding what he wanted to do, Cheeto finally cached his meal and flew back to me. In moments like this where he is upset because of the ravens, I have a more difficult time getting him to relax and come to the lure. His instinct to carry is strong in fight or flight situations. So in this scenario I just stayed near him to deter the ravens and waited for him to come to me when he wanted to. The last thing I needed was for me to push him too much and have him fly off and then get attacked by the ravens where I can’t help. Being a tiny bird is tough and dangerous. And a group of ravens could kill him if they get the chance. All is well, and I’ve come to figure out when I should try to recall him back to me quickly and when I should give him more time and space.

Let’s talk anthropomorphism. It’s a topic I like to touch on a lot, and for good reason. Anthropomorphism is attributing human characteristics onto non-humans such as animals or objects.

Anyone who works with animals must learn the body language and natural behaviors of the species they work with. As a trainer, I am constantly observing the tiniest behaviors from the birds I am interacting with. A slight change in feather posture can give a lot of information about how the bird is reacting to a situation!

When it comes to social media, millions of people can view a window of time in a video of an animal doing something. And most of the people commenting and viewing this snapshot in time do not have the knowledge of the individual animal’s history, and often they do not have knowledge of what is and is not a natural behavior for the species in general. What you then find is people projecting human emotions onto the animal instead. So often you see criticism of an animal that is displaying calm and content behaviors. And you will also see praise towards an animal that is actually stressed or injured!  Anthropomorphism does not help in any way, and it often leads people to have interactions with animals that are detrimental. This can look like someone petting an injured wild animal to “comfort” it for example. Just because an animal is being still or tolerating something, does not mean it is enjoying the interaction.

If you are an animal lover, it is a great practice to try and understand the animals you interact with from a scientific viewpoint. Learning the animal’s natural behaviors, and interacting in a way that is in the animal’s best interest. It is actually a very interesting area of study!

What is falconry?  Falconry is defined as the taking of wild quarry in its natural state and habitat by means of a trained raptor. Falconers become licensed to do this, and they must follow the laws and regulations of the area where they live.

There are so many diverse ways that people practice falconry all over the world. Different landscapes, game species, raptor species, flight styles. In general, falconers choose what kind of bird to fly based on the habitat they have and the game available to them to hunt. This could look like a red-tailed hawk hunting squirrels, a merlin hunting starlings, or a peregrine falcon hunting ducks.  The falconer’s role in this dynamic is to be a hunting partner to the raptor, and the relationship between the human and bird is built off of positive experiences. Depending on the falconer’s goals, sometimes a bird is flown for a season or two and released, sometimes birds are flown for their lifetime with the falconer, and sometimes birds are able to be utilized in other endeavors like education or propagation. Falconry is a unique window into the world of a bird of prey. It has some of the highest highs and lowest lows, and certainly there is always something new to learn.

This time of year many birds are molting, which means they are slowly dropping old feathers and growing in new ones. Growing in new feathers takes extra energy and nutrients, and the spring/summer is an ideal time of year for birds to expend this extra energy since temperatures are warmer and food is more plentiful. Molting can cause behavioral changes, especially when flying. If a bird has lost many feathers at once for example, flights become more difficult for the bird. Certainly birds fly year round even through the molt, as only some feathers are lost at a time gradually. However, depending on the types and amount of feathers missing, certain flight styles are more challenging to execute mid-molt.  Many species molt completely once a year, replacing any old, weak, and damaged feathers with new ones.

When it comes to animal training, it’s easy to get in the mindset of just putting up with problem behaviors instead of fixing them. 

“My parrot always bites me when I try to put him to bed.” “My dog is always fearful when someone comes to the door.” “My bird never goes into the travel crate easily.”

You then get a cycle of negative interactions and rehearsing unwanted behaviors, sometimes escalating the very behaviors you don’t want. It becomes more and more difficult. Instead of accepting that a behavior will always be a bad experience, you have the power to change it!  Train what you DO want the animal to do. Don’t just put up with a routine that is unpleasant for both the animal and human. If what you are doing isn’t working, change it!

Every single interaction we have with an animal influences what will happen next time. If I am near a bird that is fearful of me and I leave when the bird exhibits aggressive behavior, I am teaching the bird that aggression gets me to go away. The thing it wanted. Even if this is unintentional on my part. The smallest interactions can have a big impact on an animal’s behavior. 

It is always a goal of mine to be able to offer the animal something that it wants in return for the behavior I am looking for. My interactions are very intentional, and they are constantly changing based on what I observe the animal doing in response to me. I want the animal to look forward to good things happening in my presence.

Tactile interaction with raptors can be a hot topic. Let’s take a look at the origins of this behavior.

In general, raptors do not like to be pet. It is largely a foreign behavior to them to be “cuddly” although there are exceptions. Some birds, especially human imprints, may actually enjoy touch from people.  But this depends on the individual, the type of touch, and the context. Allopreening (social grooming) naturally occurs in certain species including some owls, vultures, and others. So situations do occur where raptors find human touch to be a positive interaction. They may even solicit for it.

Every behavior serves a purpose. Touching certain areas on a bird such as on the back can stimulate sexual arousal and naturally occur during mating and courtship. Touch around the head and face that can commonly be observed in allopreening may serve the purpose of strengthening a pair bond between mates or reducing aggression. Fluffy chicks in the nest cuddle against one another for warmth and protection. These are all natural behaviors that we can observe in birds under human care as well. The issue becomes how we interpret these behaviors. Does a baby bird that is being raised as an imprint and snuggles against you “love you”? Or is it simply acting as it would in the nest with siblings.  At times, an abnormally tame bird may even be ill and require treatment.

I want my birds to be as comfortable around me as possible. Having a bird that allows touch serves many benefits such as changing equipment without stress, health checks, or even emergency situations. This is something I train for with the birds I am handling. I find great value in having a bird that I am able to touch if need be. Most of the time, this is simply the bird knowing that I am not a threat. The bird may show no signs of stress, but that alone does not equate to enjoyment.  I have also worked with some raptors that found touch to be a rewarding interaction. It completely depends on the species and individual.

It is important to be mindful of how we utilize tactile interactions with birds and how we interpret their responses. The more we understand, the better we can implement our methods.

Last season I worked for months figuring out what process worked for trading Cheeto off a kill without him carrying. Carrying is a natural behavior that helps birds like aplomados stay safe with their food from other predators, where the bird takes its catch somewhere else to eat. And these birds can very easily have problems with carrying in a falconry setting. I put soooo much work into it last season, and apparently it’s all gone. So I will need to start over and figure it out again. Frustrating but it is what it is. While I’m glad to see he is catching prey pretty well already this season, I need the whole process to go smoothly each time. 

Yesterday Cheeto started carrying his kill around and he ended up going onto the garage roof, a favorite spot of his. No big deal, I usually just wait for him to eat or cache, and he comes right back. He wasn’t hungry enough to eat what he had caught, so he kept just standing there holding it in his foot. As it got dark, two owls began swooping at him and I needed to make moves before he got eaten. In the end I had to carefully retrieve him from the roof without upsetting him into flying away again. All is well, but I have some training ahead of me. I have had plenty of very challenging moments with Cheeto, and it isn’t all as fun and easy as it looks.

Cheeto loves to take his kill to the highest boulder to eat, especially when he catches a smaller bird like a sparrow. This makes it very obvious to other predators in the area that he is there with something delicious in his feet. Other raptors like red tails will take the opportunity to kill him and/or steal his catch if they are able. In fact, on Tuesday he had a pretty close call with a red tail that came after him as he was plucking his catch on a boulder. Luckily I was close enough to him to scare off the hawk just as it was swooping in on him. 

It can be difficult to fly a micro with so many dangers. Sometimes it takes me time to get to Cheeto when he has caught something far away. And if he is eating on a boulder, I can’t just rush in on him or he would fly off. It’s all a careful process, and no day out is 100% safe. He has learned a lot about flying around wild raptors, but he is not always smart enough to hide with his kill somewhere less obvious. He has had some close calls with red tails, coopers, peregrines, and great horned owls.  Being prepared as best I can each day has helped me greatly.

I’ve flown a lot of struggle birds the past few seasons. Dwight (my dark red tail) had an ongoing parasite problem that took me a long time to solve. He had some successes here and there but it was a lot of stress. After he was cured and released, I raised Cheeto as a baby. In that same season I also started flying Lola the ferruginous hawk. Another great bird, but quite challenging as well. The limited places suited to fly her and the lack of game made for an incredible amount of effort for very few opportunities. It was beyond frustrating to see her do everything I wanted and not put up rabbits for her. 

All of these struggles have led me here, flying the right species for the habitat I have. Accipiters like goshawks and Cooper’s hawks are able to more successfully navigate the challenging cover and terrain where I live. And for the first time I’m actually having a lot of fun going out hawking. Platinum is a fantastic bird, trained and flown by my husband last year. I couldn’t ask for a better bird to learn with as my first goshawk. While it is still difficult to find game consistently, we are doing our best and I’m learning a lot!

Flashlight training has been a vital tool for me more than once with Cheeto. This means he will fly to me in the dark illuminated by flashlight. Yesterday Cheeto stole a partially eaten quail from a Cooper’s hawk, which is a super dangerous decision on his part. Raptors steal food from each other often, and falconry birds will be robbed from their catches too. But rarely would I expect an aplomado to successfully take food from a coopers, which could easily have killed him if it wanted to. I was standing at the top of a rocky ravine, when I saw Cheeto pumping his wings hard after something across to the other side. I assumed a quail. In the distance I could barely see that he was chasing a Cooper’s hawk, and both birds made contact and fell down into the brush briefly. I heard Cheeto yell, and I saw the coopers emerge and fly away, but no Cheeto. He didn’t respond to my calls, and as I started to run down the difficult cliff side, I was sure I would be finding an injured or dead Cheeto. To my surprise when I finally got to him, there he was happily eating the leftovers that the coop clearly didn’t want very badly. He was in a spooky mood after that and started carrying the quail all over the place. For 45 minutes I attempted to retrieve him as he moved from cliff side to cliff side. Climbing up and down huge rocky slopes.  Finally he came to me in the dark with my flashlight and traded off his food for a whole quail I brought. It could easily be a death sentence to leave a tiny bird like him out overnight with all of the wild owls. So my actions in that moment are crucial.

Not every day out is fun, and there is a lot of danger out there especially with a tiny bird like an aplomado. Knowing what to do in the moment can be a life or death decision. For now all is well. 😅 And I am exhausted.
